<h1 id="anchor">Acquisition profile of FID Study of Religion</h1>
<p>The profile for the acquisitions, mainly for monographs and anthologies, is based on the classification scheme of &ldquo;Science of Religion&rdquo;.</p>
<p>Scientific literature on the following categories published main Western European languages, but &ndash; on request &ndash; also in lesser known languages is acquired by FID Religionswissenschaft.</p>

<p>Method and theory</p>
<ul>
    <li>History of the Study of Religion</li>
    <li>History of religion, sociology of religion, psychology of religion,  etc.</li>
    <li>Method, definition </li>
    <li>Theory, Philosophy of Religion</li>
    <li>Comparative studies</li>
</ul>

<p>Regional context</p>
<ul>
    <li>Comparative literature on religions in a region*</li>
    <li>Interregional Religions / Worldviews</li>
    <li>New Religious Movements (NRM) </li>
    <li>Other ideological associations </li>
</ul>
<sub>*Works on individual major religions outside Europe are not included in the acquisition profile of FID Study of Religion, due to a possible overlap with the collection profiles of regional FID (e.g. FID Middle East, North Africa and Islamic studies or CROSSASIA).</sub>

<p>Textual / Conceptual Context</p>
<ul>
    <li>Comparative literature on religious texts*</li>
    <li>Literature on ethnic religions</li>
    <li>Criticism of religion, non-religion, atheism, etc.</li>
    <li>Debates (e.g. Religion vs. Science)</li>
</ul>
<sub>*Not acquired is exegetical-philological literature of individual religions</sub>